segments.text: Did you like teaching?
Oh, yes.
Now that you're on the other side here.
Very much so.
I alluded to something about mass punishment earlier in our talk.
The cadet wing
Air Force Wing saw fit to campus all of its juniors at one time.
What happened, somebody let the air out of all the seniors' tires.
The seniors had a parking lot, they may still have, where only seniors could park.
So somebody let the air out of their tires.
And all the seniors got together and they camped with the juniors.
Well, at that time, I was the
senior instructor for Air Science 4, which are the seniors.
And I had three, four other instructors who were also teaching Air Science 4.
And I said, now, I'm getting ready to do something.
I don't want you to criticize what I'm doing.
I'm not asking that you do it.
And if you're questioned by any of your students, just
make some remark, well, I haven't even thought about that, or I haven't heard about it, or whatever you want to say.
Just don't get in the act.
So, first class, I walk in, and of course they come to attention.
Good morning, gentlemen.
This morning, before we take up the lesson for the day, we're going to have a standby inspection of uniform.
I just went down the line and said, mister, I said,
Isn't your tie tucked in at the wrong place?
Doesn't it belong between the second and third button?
Yes, sir.
Okay, that's two diversions.
Everybody in here says that's two diversions.
Take a seat.
I had three sections.
Second section came along, same thing.
Mister, don't you have on the wrong color sock?
I've never seen that color sock with a uniform.
Yes, sir.
That's it.
Non-rigged socks, that's two demerits, isn't it?
Yes, sir.
I said, everyone in the section is assessed two demerits.
Take your seats.
Third section came along, did the same thing.
When the first section came back to class two days later, good morning, gentlemen.
We're going to have a standby inspection again this morning.
The wing commander was in that class.
He said, sir, may I speak?
I said, yes, sir.
I said, Major, are you trying to tell us that mass punishment is wrong?
I said, well, it didn't take you long to learn, did it?
He said, well, for your information, we have released the juniors from their restriction to campus.
I said, for your information, all those who are still on my desk may have gone to the Commandant's office.
Get your ass out of here and go find out who let the air out of your tires and then punish them to the hilt.
And it worked.
Not only those three sections, but it spread through all the other sections.
Well, I had some real interesting times.
I was the sponsor of Squadron 7.
Squadron 7
may not be what it used to be.
But at that time, it was the top unit on the campus.
I mean, scholastically, intramurally, it just took all of the trophies.
And this was two years, the first two years I was there.
And one day this Colonel John Way, who was a professor of air science, said, you know, when you're on top,
It's easy to stay on top.
I said, why don't you go get something that you don't have?
I said, you name it, Colonel.
What is it?
He says, let's see you take the Houston military away from that infantry outfit.
We'll do it.
So I went down to squadron seven and called us cadet officers in.
I said, you've got a challenge, because I'm going to give you the challenge.
And I've got the challenge because the colonel put it on me.
I said, we're going to win the Houston military.
God, our outfit could never win that.
Hell, it can't.
And of course, the march-ins at football games are graded, and certain march-ins to the dining hall are graded.
Everything military goes to the Houston military.
Sure enough, Mother's Day, when it was announced, Squadron 7, Houston military.
Well...
That year I had a compassionate reassignment from A&M up to that Aviation Engineer Force because one of our children was sick and ultimately died.
When Final Review came around, have you ever seen a Final Review before?
When Final Review came around and
First time they came around, you know, they saluted the commandant and all that business.
And then they all went back out and got in the huddle, you know, and they put on their bars and everything, you know, and turned everything over to the juniors, and the juniors stepped up.
They came walking across that field, and they handed me four sets of ropes, and it was all of them, the scholastic, the intramural, whatever the other one was, and then the Houston military.
They said, here, Major.
We know you can't wear them, but you can do something with them.
And we had just built up a spree that, by golly, I stepped back, and they ran their outfit, and they came to me when they needed help, when they wanted something.
And it was just one of the greatest things that had ever happened to me.
A bunch of cadets were doing it.
But...
That old professor, he said, I never thought it would happen.
I said, John, all you've got to do is just have a good bunch of cadets.
He was from Oklahoma.
I said, now you Hokies just don't understand.
He died here last year.
Were you sorry to leave AM99 after three years?
Or were you ready for a transfer?
Oh, I think we were ready.
Our daughter contracted polio and an epidemic they had up there.
She ultimately died of bronchial pneumonia.
But I was ready to get moving and let's start.
So your next assignment then was Director of Operations, Aviation, Engineering, Engineer Force, which you had from 1955 to 1956.
Now, what were your functions there?
And where was it first?
Well, the Aviation Engineer Force was
there at Walters, Mineral Wells.
Oh, okay.
Yeah.
Which you talked about.
Right.
Yeah.
And Navigation Engine Air Force is exactly what it said.
It was, believe it or not, it was a bunch of Army troops that also had Air Force enlisted personnel and Air Force officers assigned to them.
And they were under the control of the Air Force under a term called SCARWAW.
Special Category Army with Air Force.
And they were dedicated solely to construction of Air Force installations and bases and wherever the Air Force wanted them to go.
And I had both operations and then at one time planned the program, which was

worldwide assignment and utilization, war and peace, and figuring out how many battalions, regiments, brigades were needed in various parts of the country to support whatever the mission was and how many flying units we had.
I guess one of the most interesting projects that we worked on, though, was I had an Army captain and an Air Force captain working for me, and we put together a manual that had never been assembled.

I mean, you could go here and get this and here and get that, but we assembled a manual that could actually be carried onto a job, and it was recovery of an Air Force installation following nuclear attack.
so that they didn't have to carry a library as big as that over there.
They just carried one manual, and the whole thing was there.
And it took us about six months to put the thing together, and it was ultimately published.
And even though they abolished SCARWOF, and all those Army troops went back to the Army, and our Air Force went back into our own engineering units, base maintenance units,
We still buy copies of the manual around.
Of course, this was a period when the atomic bomb and, well, when we were building up our atomic arsenal.
Was there a lot of interest within the Air Force at this time?
Oh, yeah, very definitely.
I used to kid my contemporaries that

If I went over to the Planning and Programming Office, over on one corner of the desk, I had worldwide utilization of aviation engineer forces, and then over on this, return of SCARWAC units to the Army.

If a breeze came along and mixed these papers, you know, well, that was the biggest job we had for months, because here we were planning how to use these guys for years in a war and peace, and over here,
I'll give them back to the Army within 30 days.
But you go through that quite often.
Of course, this is a time when the Air Force is enlarging, and we're getting now into strategic air command.
Were you building a lot of air bases at this time?
Yeah.

because of the agreements with the labor and so on, these units would stay in a training status most of the time, but could be used downrange, down the Bahamas, in Iceland, and we could use them in the Pacific, but not in
the Connus in the continental United States because that was to be left open for bidding on the economy.
What were the major bases that you built?
Well, no base per se, but additional facilities at Thule, for instance, at Hickam itself.
So you were back in the construction field.
Yeah.
And at Tachikawa in Japan, at Clark.
Did you have any dealings with any of the building that was going on in the new line, any of the Canadian strategic defenses at that time?
No, I didn't at that time.
I did later on, but not at that time.

of course this is a time with the enlargement of the strategic air command did you have any dealings with any construction as far as they were concerned no see most of theirs were caught us and they'd be under contract under contract okay and of course this is the 50s was an era when general curtis lemay was

very influential in the airport did you ever have an opportunity to meet him or see him i have not only met the general i have briefed him i've helped dressed him really oh yeah oh would you tell me about that well when i say i helped dress him later in in the career let's see that'd be three four four years after this
Air Force, when LeMay was chief of staff, I had to brief General LeMay.
General Bradley was then the vice chief.
And he said, now, remember, speak directly to him.
And don't look at me, because he's hard of hearing, and he will not wear a hearing aid.
But be distinct.
Of course, I'd had all of this already, and it didn't bother me because I had reached bigger people in LeMay.
LeMay comes in to the room, and he leans over like this to sit down, and these four stars had come on the hook, and they just started swinging like this.
And he looked like a roar of Boer Alice.
There were so many stars just swinging through the air.
And I said, gentlemen, your stars are falling.
Your stars are falling.
God damn, this little man didn't get those things fixed right.
Here, hook him up.
So with that, I don't know whether you heard the rest of the briefing or not.
We had a
We've jumped four years, but he's a very outspoken man, which is great.
By the way, he was an Ohio State civil engineer.
I don't know whether you knew that or not, but even engineers become pretty good leaders.
We were getting ready to modernize the officer's club at Bowling.
There were a couple of concepts as to how to do it.
And oh boy, we're seven or eight years ahead now.
Because by that time, I was in the Secretary of the Air Force office.
And there was a group in his office with a model of the officer's club.
And there must have been about 16 or 18 officers, including me.
They got to talking about the concept.
And now, see, here everybody works for him except me, and I work for the Secretary of the Air Force.
And one of these guys says, General LeMay, Mr. Zuckert, who is the Secretary of the Air Force, Mr. Zuckert thinks that we ought to do so-and-so.
Oh, you know that stuff.
Oh, you go tell Mr. Zuckert to piss off a rope.
Now he's talking about my boss.
And about half those eyes look at me like, what's Zucker going to do?
He was exactly what was needed at the time.
Capable individual.
Not afraid to speak out.
I'm sure that we bought time with a lot of his boldness, his bluff, and that we needed.
Was there a friction between the Strategic Air Command and other parts of the Air Force?
Always is.
Why?
Well, you trace as a rule who would go to the top.
to run the Air Force, you'd always find that they came out of the strategic command.
Strategic air command would graduate to the top.
And training command and tactical air command did never make it up.
They'd make it so high, but they'd never get to the top.
And so that's most of it.
That is not really where most of the animosity and friction really is.
There are other places that have friction.
In our business,
And it didn't bother me, because I wore a blue suit.
But remember I said earlier that at West Point, when you graduated, and they rank the class, and then everybody gets to pick what branch they want to go into.
The top of the class usually picks the Corps of Engineers.
It's a good honorable profession and it provides you something to do after you leave the service.
It's a damn good service to be in.
And then they go on down the line.
And the bottom is the infantry.
Well, years ago this happened and still does.
And so
before the Air Force had its own academy, before the Air Force started building its own system, this guy would say, I'm going to aviation cadets before I go to the infantry.
OK, now you've got a guy that's down here in the bottom quarter of the class that went to aviation cadets instead of going to the infantry.
which he would have had to done, because there was none of this other choice assignments left.

He comes out of aviation cadets, and all these guys go along for 25 years, and now here you got, at the top of the Air Force, a guy that was in the bottom quarter of the class, and you got this engineer group sitting over here that was at the top of the class, and they're just like that.
Now, it's getting better as we get our own people out of the Air Force Academy.
Because we're not getting as many of this bottom quarter coming out of West Point or coming out of Annapolis or Point.
Let me tell you, it was rough.
I mean, again, not me, because I'm wearing blue.
But you go in to brief one of these commanders and tell him,
The core, don't tell me about the core.
Just, you know, turn themselves off.
I don't believe it.
You go back over there and you tell that core, you know.
There's just a lot of animosity in between.
And, you know, you can expect it.
It's built in.
I mean, it's there.
Anytime you've got the rank and file system, and they can carry it for years.
Well, we jumped from a... Well, I wanted to ask about the Mayan SAC because these things are very important as far as the history of the Air Force is concerned.
And they're always interested in problems or the relationship between some people who aren't in the Strategic Air Command and those who are.
Well, fortunately, we've got a thing right now that is going to help
We have a four-star general in command of the training command whose headquarters is here at Randolph.
And on the 28th of this month, he moves to Sac, and he takes over Sac.
And he happens to be the youngest four-star general in the Air Force.
He's only 52 years old.
So he's got some years to go.
And conceivably, General Davis will someday be the chief of staff.
We've got to remember that he made his fourth star at training command, not at SAC, and quite a capable individual.
What we've got, believe it or not right now, is we've got a little tug and push and shove between research and developers and tacticians.
Sure.
And that's not all bad.
Not all bad.
If the research and developers can come up with some fancy beam warfare that makes it quicker and saves a hell of a lot of lives, why should the tacticians always have the principles of war
boss comes and matches the first one, you don't always need matches.
Okay, so then you went to France right after that in 1956.
That was terrific.
Were you eager to get overseas again?
Well, I hadn't been overseas.
They offered me Alaska or France and though in my master's study at A&M I studied
Creopediology, which is permafrost, I chose France.
A little bit nicer place to live.
A little more action.
The organizations are larger.
You got a two-star in command in Alaska.
You got a four-star in command in Europe.
I think your chances are better in Europe.
We went over and
I was a resident engineer at two bases.
One has already been completed, but we were lengthening the runway and doing some more facility work.
Where was that?
That was Shomal.
Shomal happens to be one of the locations that Black Jack Pershing had his headquarters during World War I. Shomal, Sur Marne, the Marne River.
The other one was Shalon Battery, which was a brand new base that had only a runway and a few facilities.
And it was a NATO base.
That's what NATO gave us here, a runway and a few facilities.
And we were pouring American dollars into building another base.
And that's where I spent most of my time.

My deputy was an Army civil servant, and I worked with the French ,, which is roads and bridges, who was the contracting officer to the French contractors, even though the work was being done for us and paid for by us.
they left the contract.
And it was strictly the rapport that he and I maintained as to how much pressure we put on the contractors to deliver what was right and so on.
And we ended up, even though I was not there when it was completed, I hadn't been moved to Africa by then, but a very, very minimum of claims from the contractor.
At that time, I worked for an Army colonel.
So I was, again, mixed into this joint service thing.
And I truthfully must say, just by having lived the Corps life and being able to adjust to just about anything, I don't care whether the guy's Army, Navy, or what.
what the guy produces, how he treats people.
Anyway, we got along fine.
At this time, of course, France was still in NATO, and they pulled out a few years after that.
How are the relations with the French army, or the French officers?
Great.
Great?
Still great?
Yeah.
In 56 and 57?
Yep.
Terrific.
Yeah, the fact is, you see, on that whole tour, I felt this because, like you say, how it was in relation then.

Then when I left there and went down to North Africa for a short period of time and I went to England, that's where I really felt it because when we pulled out of England, I mean pulled out of France, we brought them to England, you see.
Because there we brought the units that we pulled out of France.
We brought them in to England.
And that's where we had nuke storage rights.
And I got to England just in time to start programming and building up facilities for those units that just two or three years ahead I had helped facilitate over there in France.
Chaumont actually moved from
The unit at Chaumont, where the 48th Fighter moved from there to Lake and Heath, England.
Again, I made the statement, the French individual is great.
Collectively, they're a bunch of bums.
Especially if they're on the highway.
Boy, they're horrible.
They're the worst drivers I've ever seen.
And in downtown Paris.
How many people did you have working for you when you were a resident engineer here in France?
About 9 or 10, I guess.
And were they engineers?
Yeah.
Yes.
And they were both American and French.
Oh.
Yeah.
And so how would it work?
The Air Force would say, okay, we want you to go build this landing strip or something like that, or go build a building on this base, and then you'd sit down and draw the plans?
No, we did not design it.
All we did was just supervise the construction.
Oh, okay.
The plans came to us from our own organization in Paris.
Okay.
That was the joint construction they were headed by.
Well, it would alternate.
One term it would be an Army guy, the next term it would be a Navy, and the next term it would be an Air Force.
And then it would just keep rotating.
And it was called the Joint Construction Agency.
Everybody in there was just a mixture.
Is this Joint Construction Agency?
Is that a fairly new output?
No, it's no longer in existence.
It's no longer OK. Yeah.
Tell me a little bit about that.
I mean, when did they start this agency?
I've never seen it.
OK. Let's see.
We went over and they started just for the task.
Why do they have this agency?
They started just for the task of building bases?
Let's see.
We went over.
It must have started about 51 or 52.
And when we left there to go down to Africa, it was phasing down then.
And the only reason they pulled me out early is the
officer that I had worked for at the Aviation and Air Force asked for me in Africa.
He was down there.
And he asked, he says, since you're phasing down, can you send Johnson to me now?
He'd been trying for a year to get me down here.
And so they finally said, yeah, we'll let him go.
Now, why did they even have this agency, the Joint Construction Agency?
Just to explain, why did they even institute it?
I can't answer the question with 100% assurance that I'm right, because there was so much demand for construction throughout, I have to remember where all it was now, in Italy.

in Greece, Spain, in Germany, in France, that somebody made the decision that it was bigger than the Corps of Engineers could handle on its own, and that the Navy ought to have a voice in it, and the Air Force ought to have a voice in it,
especially when it affected their own civil combat agency.
So they formed this thing.
Now, when it fell apart at the time I went to Africa, then it went back to Army everywhere in Europe except England, and that belongs to the Air Force, and the Navy in Spain.
And the Army has all the rest of it, even now.
So the building then, they had accomplished the mission of that building in those six or seven years that it was in existence.
And then they decided to phase it out, and the Corps could handle whatever building was necessary.
OK. All right.
So you went to Libya in 1957 as the director engineer.
And construction, engineering and construction.
I had 36 people working for me there.
And we had.
Did they give you a promotion or not?
No, I was still a major.
I made Lieutenant Colonel while there.
We had Morocco, Libya, Italy, Greece, and Turkey.
That's where our units were scattered, in those five countries.
Well, it wasn't too bad.
We had one base in Italy.
We had one base in Greece, we had two in Morocco, we had one in Libya, but we had about five or six in Turkey and Crete.
A good bit of traveling then.
So did you travel around from base to base doing any, you know, anytime they needed some construction?
Yeah.
Were there major operations?
We handled two different types of operations.
At that time, a minor construction project was something that ran from $25,000 to $100,000.
And that we could design, and if the command had the money, commit the money and go.
If it was major construction, it had to go before the Congress for congressional approval and appropriation.
We would work with the programmers to define it, and the programmers would put it on the documents and get it on up the line and then get it approved.
Once it was approved, then we would work with the Corps of Engineers to see that they designed what we intended to have built.
and they'd take over and finish the design, let the contract, supervise the contract, and then we would run the acceptance inspection and so on.
So it's kind of a split operation.
It's part of what the magnitude was.
Like a big hangar at Tripoli, Libya, Wheeler.
All that we did was define the project and say, this is what we want, and then look over the core shoulder and say, OK, we agree with the design.
Build it.
And then they'd build it.
Did Mrs. Johnson get to go with you to Libya?
Yes, and both boys.
We have two boys.
So she was in France with you and in Libya, and then in the United Kingdom?
Yeah.
Oh, good.
So what were the conditions like in Libya?
Well, when we were there they were great because we moved right into the first place we lived was a brand new masonry house.
So new that it hadn't even seasoned and you could be sitting like we are here talking and least little rise in temperature and something would go.
And a seed would pop out of a little plaster.
They hadn't used clean sand, and it was a grass seed, you know.
We'd be talking some more, and something would go... And another one would pop out up there.
But all in all, they were good.
And we moved from there to another, what they call, villa.
And then, ultimately, we moved on base in the base quarters.
We had...
I'd say an above average houseboy.
The women don't work down there.
The men work.
You can do the domestic work.
We found it pretty interesting.
It gave my older boy, or our older boy, a challenge in life and an outlook that has led to his profession.
He is a graduate of American University.
International Relations and his postgraduate master's degree from the University of Utah.
He is a Persian expert.
He speaks Arabic, Fazi, French, as well as English.
He happens to be a major in the Air Force.
That is interesting.
And this is where he picked up that interest.
That first challenge.
Well, why did you only stay there for about a year and then go to the United Kingdom in 1959?
The tour in Libya is what they call a short tour.
And I offered them a short extension in Libya or a long extension in the United Kingdom.
And the personnel people and the civil engineer people got to wrestling.
And they said, well, under the conditions, what's happening in the United Kingdom?
let's move into the United Kingdom.
And what was happening that they needed to?
That's when these units in France were being programmed into England and into Germany.
Okay, let's talk about this.
I've heard some interesting comments about when we moved out of France.
Okay, the project of the move of
Air Force units from France to England was called Red Richard.
That was the code word.
It was an unclassified code word.
But anything that was Red Richard, everybody knew money-wise, program-wise, that was to get a unit or had to do with moving from France to the United Kingdom.
And I was
titled Director of Project Management.

I had master planning, planning, programming, and fiscal control under me in the United Kingdom in civil engineering, which put me right in sitting with the commanders and the engineers and the general from headquarters Air Force Europe that
with the units moving out as to what they needed and what had to be done to the bases that, you know, that they were designated to go to and so on.
What we had to do with emergency money, which is, you know, the money that we had right now that we could use, what we had to go back to Congress to get approval on and so on.
But the project was called Red Richard.
And it was just one of those all-night, all-day things.
You get it done and...
What were the feelings toward the French in your command at this time?
Well, I think the feeling in our command, being on the continent, those units weren't in our command.
They were in the 16th Air Force, I guess it was.
And everybody in the United Kingdom was in the 3rd Air Force.
Well, they weren't our units until they moved to us.
You know, in the United Kingdom, it was kind of nice a lot.
But the overall feeling was that, you know, the French have really slipped through, after all.
For years, we've been pouring money into there.
And for years, they've been part of the program.
And now, this has happened.
But even now, today, in 81, you know, they're not completely out of it.
No.
You know?
It's a crazy agreement or arrangement, but it's been harmful to the total force, but we've lived with it.
I've heard some comments from other generals saying that when the American forces moved out of France and moved everything, even the telephones and everything that they could, it was at the...
Was that the order that came down from Tom?
Well... Or was that just resentment?
No.
I wouldn't say it was resentment.
I'd say that was, you know, move whatever you can.
You know, you've got to make this move with the least amount of additional expenditure.
At Chambord, when we first got to France as a resident engineer and
Our first quarters were on Showmont.
Later we moved over near the other base.
That weekend or the very next weekend, they dedicated a Statue of Liberty that bronze or brass was about that tall, standing on a pedestal that was again about that tall.
And that thing had been built from the pattern that the statue is made in the New York Harbor.
But when that unit moved from Showmont to Lake and Heath, they even took the Statue of Liberty with them.
Vive la France, and we're back to help in all this business.
And then two years later, you can stay, but your nukes have got to go.
Well, what does a nuclear force do?
Where did you store the nuclear weapons that America had in France?
Yeah, did we store them back in Great Britain?
Oh, yeah.
Yeah, we've got terrific storage facilities in Britain.
And did you help construct those?
Oh, yeah.
Some of the units, though, now went to Germany.
All of them did not go to England.
We picked up there were, in France, there was nuclear either three or four wings.
We got two of them in
and Germany got through them.
The rest were transported out.
The pressure wasn't on on them.
They ultimately moved them out also.
The pressure was to maintain the nuclear force in Europe.
Was there special problems with building sites where you could store nuclear weapons?
No.
But we already had them.
We already had nuclear weapons in England.
And so you just, you didn't have to expand them, they were large enough?
No, they had to be expanded.
Bases were, like we had a combination of Bentwater's Woodbridge, two bases about six miles apart,
that one wing had.
It had two squadrons on one location and one on the other.
We put another squadron in there that belonged to one of these outfits coming in.
So you build up a little more facility.
But fortunately in England, where we have ammo and nuke storage, the British had pretty good foresight and put sufficient clearance around them.
So was that your major task when you were in England for those two years, 1959 and 1960?
Yeah, I guess it was for that period.
Two interesting things happened then.
You asked earlier, way back there before A&M, I happened to be the district commissioner of the Mayflower District of the Boy Scouts of America.
And that was just made up of Boy Scout units in the United Kingdom.
So that was a freebie job, a service job.
And the man that I worked for in England during that time period was the first one that
my own effectiveness report ever since.
